EPA also requires preparation of an Alternate Release Scenario (ARS) for each category as applicable.  The ARS uses more realistic or plausible assumptions, such as a pipe or valve failure.



For the flammable WCS, Countrymark used Iso-butane which is generally similar to propane which is also stored on-site.



ACCIDENTAL RELEASE PREVENTION



CountryMark previously implemented a comprehensive program to prevent accidental releases of highly hazardous chemicals under the U.S. Occupational Safety and Health Agency (OSHA) Process Safety Management (PSM) Program.  CountryMark's PSM program ensures that proper safety information is in place; operating procedures are followed; chemical hazards are identified; employees and contractors are trained; and critical equipment is inspected and maintained.  The OSHA PSM program satisfies the EPA's RMP requirements.  Note of interest CountryMark underwent an approximate 3 month long PSM inspection by OSHA from November of 2008 to the first part of 2009.Since CountryMark has substantially upgraded it's HAZOP program.



Some of the many, specific procedures in place to prevent a chemical accident include:



A?    Safety procedures that reduce the potential for human error leading to a tank overfill;

A?    Routine pipe and vessel inspection and testing;

A?    Safety information about the processes available to employees;

A?    Written operating procedures that include emergency response actions;

A?    Employee and contractor awareness training programs to promote consistently safe work practices;

