nce programs to ensure ongoing equipment reliability;

A?    Compliance auditing to ensure standards are being followed;

A?    Incorporation of PSM (Management of Change) review procedures;

A?    Safety reviews prior to start-up of our processes;

A?    Full implementation of OSHA permit required programs.



FIVE YEAR ACCIDENT HISTORY



EPA's RMP regulation requires that any incidents involving regulated chemicals that resulted in any off-site impact or significant on-site impacts be reported in this document.   The CountryMark refinery has not had any incidents and/or releases in regards to RMP regulated chemicals in the past five years.  



EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROGRAM



CountryMark refinery maintains a comprehensive emergency response program designed to protect employees, the public and the environment in the event of a hazardous material incident.  All refinery employees receive emergency response training.  Operations employees receive additional response training for particular units on their rotation.  



We maintain a trained Fire Response Brigade with response equipment matched to the unique hazards of a petroleum refinery.   We are active members of the Mt. Vernon Industrial Mutual Aid and River Spill Response Mutual Aid groups.  We have employees who are active volunteer firefighters, are on the local ALERT Committee, and the RMP related Posey County LEPC Committee.



PLANNED CHANGES TO IMPROVE SAFETY



CountryMark has an ongoing Behavior Based Safety Program that is meant to support the Environmental, Safety and Health Policies.  Our safety oversight program monitors and tracks training, incident investigations, performance audits and other related activities designed to reduce overall risks.  It is our intention to continue this program and further develop our risk management efforts.  We also work closely with our insurers and risk underwriters to evaluate and plan on physical changes that may further reduce inherent facility hazards and risks.   Written e
